sentences: Peter Oelrichs Duchin (born July 28, 1937) is an American pianist and band leader.
Duchin formed his first professional band, which played the St. Regis Hotel in New York City, in 1962 thanks in part to his family name and the networking it had made possible.
His single "Star Dust" reached No. 143 in the Cashbox survey, 1964.
From 1985 to 1989, Duchin had a professional partnership with Jimmy Maxwell, leader of the traditional society jazz band in New Orleans.
By 2009, Duchin's band had played at an estimated 6,000 performances.
In 1964, he married Cheray Zauderer, a divorced Manhattan socialite with whom he eventually had three children.
After his divorce from Zauderer, in 1985 Duchin married Brooke Hayward, with whom he had been living since 1981.

In 1996 he published his memoir, Ghost of a Chance.
In 2008 Hayward and Duchin announced their separation, and they eventually divorced.
Duchin married Virginia Coleman over the 2012 Memorial Day weekend in East Hampton.

His mother was Marjorie Oelrichs, a Newport, Rhode Island and New York City socialite who died unexpectedly when he was just five days old.

The band's style and genres have been described as "a musical approach that incorporates big bands, swing and Broadway songs (and nowadays, old-fashioned rock 'n' roll)."Duchin's music was much heard on MOR radio in the late 1960s and early '70s from albums and singles released on the Decca, Bell and Capitol labels.
